WEBVTT

00:00.051 --> 00:00.112
you

00:57.002 --> 00:59.585
[SPEAKER_10]: Annyeonghaseyo!

00:59.825 --> 01:00.906
[SPEAKER_10]: How are we all?

01:00.926 --> 01:14.279
[SPEAKER_10]: It's great to see you, Your Excellencies, distinguished guests, members of the media, and importantly, our youth representatives who are here today.

01:14.780 --> 01:20.545
[SPEAKER_10]: Welcome to the 21st Jeju Forum for Peace and Prosperity.

01:25.667 --> 01:34.052
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm Sharon Jeet Lail and it is a genuine pleasure for me to be here on Jeju Island, the island of peace.

01:34.753 --> 01:42.738
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm also delighted to say that we are broadcasting live on Arirang TV and on the Jeju forums YouTube channel.

01:43.638 --> 01:52.586
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, over the next 90 minutes, we are going to be asking the question that's impacting, of course, the global community.

01:52.906 --> 02:00.012
[SPEAKER_10]: And that is, how do we reimagine multilateralism in a rapidly changing world?

02:00.753 --> 02:09.983
[SPEAKER_10]: And we'll be asking that question to the women and men who are seeking to become the next Secretary General of the United Nations.

02:10.363 --> 02:17.130
[SPEAKER_10]: They will be only the tenth leader of that organization to succeed, of course, Antonio Guterres in 2027.

02:19.205 --> 02:30.503
[SPEAKER_10]: But first, let me introduce our favorite son of South Korea, the eighth Secretary General of the United Nations, His Excellency Ban Ki-moon.

02:31.043 --> 02:32.866
[SPEAKER_10]: Excellency, the floor is yours.

03:00.477 --> 03:13.982
[SPEAKER_13]: Excellencies, distinguished guests, ladies and gentlemen, and distinguished candidates for the next Secretary General of the United Nations, welcome to you all.

03:15.683 --> 03:26.267
[SPEAKER_13]: As former Secretary General of the United Nations, it is my distinct honor to welcome you all to Jeju, the island of peace.

03:27.690 --> 03:33.632
[SPEAKER_13]: It is truly moving to witness such a gathering of visionary leaders.

03:34.872 --> 03:41.875
[SPEAKER_13]: I feel the passion that fuels your commitment to our collective future.

03:43.075 --> 03:51.918
[SPEAKER_13]: And it is my firm belief that each of you is ready to shoulder the hopes of humanity.

03:53.478 --> 03:54.679
[SPEAKER_13]: Distinguished candidates,

03:55.746 --> 04:03.988
[SPEAKER_13]: Let me begin with a candid reflection from one who has walked this path before.

04:05.048 --> 04:07.529
[SPEAKER_13]: To be honest, I don't envy you.

04:10.730 --> 04:19.752
[SPEAKER_13]: When I was campaigning for the Office of the Secretary General back in 2006, there was no such forum as this.

04:20.954 --> 04:31.138
[SPEAKER_13]: no public stage where candidates could transparently present and contest their visions before the world's people.

04:32.358 --> 04:42.662
[SPEAKER_13]: In that sense, I was fortunate, but I feel for you this is a very rigorous and demanding process.

04:43.102 --> 04:44.463
[SPEAKER_13]: Be ready for that.

04:45.563 --> 04:50.165
[SPEAKER_13]: And yet, in the same breath, I truly envy you.

04:51.694 --> 05:03.042
[SPEAKER_13]: In my time, I had to seek out every opportunity, moving from capital to capital, often in the shadow of quiet diplomacy.

05:04.243 --> 05:20.115
[SPEAKER_13]: You, however, stand here on the global stage of the Jeju Forum, where you can articulate your vision with transparency and rigor before the world.

05:22.005 --> 05:35.077
[SPEAKER_13]: That openness, the opportunity to be tested on your merits in the clear light of day is a privilege I find genuinely precious.

05:36.618 --> 05:44.445
[SPEAKER_13]: Dear candidates, people often speak of the Secretary General of the United Nations as

05:45.593 --> 05:49.996
[SPEAKER_13]: the quote, present of the world, but I don't agree with this.

05:50.897 --> 05:54.599
[SPEAKER_13]: Or the secular pope, I don't agree with this either.

05:55.059 --> 06:02.945
[SPEAKER_13]: But this is what people would say, have been saying about the post of the Secretary General of the United Nations.

06:03.807 --> 06:21.214
[SPEAKER_13]: But those who have held this position before, including myself, told now, tell the truth that S.G., which is Secretary General, is often

06:22.417 --> 06:28.278
[SPEAKER_13]: in reality, quoted as the scapegoat, scapegoat.

06:29.038 --> 06:35.680
[SPEAKER_13]: SUGs are often called scapegoat, so you should be ready to become a scapegoat.

06:37.180 --> 06:48.302
[SPEAKER_13]: The position demands an immense weight of responsibility, endless reserve of patience, and at times, profound sense of solitude.

06:49.420 --> 07:07.225
[SPEAKER_13]: And yet, I envy you because one of you will work side by side with the most dedicated people on Earth, UN staff who have pledged their lives to the cause of humanity.

07:08.906 --> 07:17.168
[SPEAKER_13]: You will share burdens in the most difficult corners of the globe, and in doing so,

07:18.770 --> 07:26.635
[SPEAKER_13]: forged bonds of fellowship that no title or salary can ever replicate.

07:27.676 --> 07:42.126
[SPEAKER_13]: You will also be supported by the diplomats, business leaders, and civil society organizations who are eager to unite behind your leadership and shape the course of history.

07:44.047 --> 07:47.550
[SPEAKER_13]: Excellencies, ladies and gentlemen, dear colleagues,

07:48.773 --> 07:51.395
[SPEAKER_13]: I know all the candidates personally.

07:51.695 --> 07:55.418
[SPEAKER_13]: I have known all of you in person, in fact, without fail.

07:56.639 --> 08:15.214
[SPEAKER_13]: Having worked alongside them for years, I can attest that whoever is elected tomorrow, he or she is fully capable of assuming this post office with distinction.

08:17.299 --> 08:25.044
[SPEAKER_13]: Looking at the road ahead, I must confess again, I do not envy you.

08:25.345 --> 08:27.546
[SPEAKER_13]: Again, this is what I'm telling you.

08:29.207 --> 08:44.738
[SPEAKER_13]: Whoever assume the office of the Secretary General of the United Nations on January 1st next year will inherit an institution facing lot of challenges of truly historic proportions.

08:45.808 --> 09:00.792
[SPEAKER_13]: The United Nations is in the grips of a serious financial crisis, its authority questioned, and its credibility strained by relentless calls for reform.

09:02.132 --> 09:10.935
[SPEAKER_13]: The war in Ukraine has entered its fifth year with no clear prospect for a peaceful resolution.

09:11.675 --> 09:15.156
[SPEAKER_13]: At the same time, the conflict in the Middle East

09:16.469 --> 09:21.151
[SPEAKER_13]: more seriously the war between the United States and Iran.

09:22.492 --> 09:41.440
[SPEAKER_13]: Though the parties have signed the peace agreement, continue to inflict a profound human and economic and geopolitical cost, devastating consequences for the countries involved and the wider world.

09:43.004 --> 09:54.269
[SPEAKER_13]: On the other hand, the climate crisis grows more urgently with every passing year, maybe every passing second or hour.

09:55.410 --> 10:09.997
[SPEAKER_13]: And now, artificial intelligence, AI, introduces a new dimension of uncertainty that our existing international frameworks are wholly unprepared to address.

10:11.294 --> 10:20.846
[SPEAKER_13]: But there is another side to this, the potential for you to write an epic chapter in the history of the United Nations.

10:21.867 --> 10:25.712
[SPEAKER_13]: In this regard, the next Secretary General of the United Nations

10:26.488 --> 10:51.069
[SPEAKER_13]: will have the rare privilege of rebuilding shattered trust in multilateralism and demonstrating convincingly and concretely that the United Nations can still make a real tangible difference in the lives of ordinary people everywhere in this world.

10:52.141 --> 10:57.764
[SPEAKER_13]: you will serve as the true architect of the global agenda.

11:00.046 --> 11:08.170
[SPEAKER_13]: I still remember the moments during my own tenure that filled me with the deepest sense of purpose.

11:09.171 --> 11:21.418
[SPEAKER_13]: The day the Paris Climate Change Agreement was adopted, the day the 17 goals of sustainable development goals were adopted and endorsed,

11:22.542 --> 11:32.251
[SPEAKER_13]: unanimously by 193 member nations, and the day when the UN Women was established.

11:33.753 --> 11:40.800
[SPEAKER_13]: Those were the days when all the UN member states were united as one.

11:41.420 --> 11:45.784
[SPEAKER_13]: I am proud to have worked with a member state and

11:46.692 --> 11:48.893
[SPEAKER_13]: diligently working UN staff.

11:49.673 --> 11:54.534
[SPEAKER_13]: You will continue to carry on these initiatives.

11:55.354 --> 12:11.518
[SPEAKER_13]: The profound realization that the single collective decision could set a positive course for billions of lives, the sense of meaning is a reward I know you too will come to cherish.

12:13.228 --> 12:20.752
[SPEAKER_13]: for you will be the ones to ignite the hope when the world needs it most.

12:21.412 --> 12:27.856
[SPEAKER_13]: In that regard, I envy you more than anyone else, so you should be ready for that.

12:29.116 --> 12:41.203
[SPEAKER_13]: Excellencies, Distinguished Foreign Minister Cho Hyun of Republic of Korea, dear candidates for the next UN Secretary General, ladies and gentlemen,

12:42.550 --> 12:53.120
[SPEAKER_13]: I myself was a child of war who, with the help of the United Nations, rose to become a man of peace.

12:54.361 --> 13:06.032
[SPEAKER_13]: The Republic of Korea rose from the ashes of the Korean War of 1950 with the vital support of the United Nations and its member states.

13:07.222 --> 13:12.830
[SPEAKER_13]: having transformed from an aid recipient into donor nations.

13:13.310 --> 13:21.662
[SPEAKER_13]: Korea is, whether you believe it or not, Korea is the only country in the world accepting all those

13:22.902 --> 13:31.286
[SPEAKER_13]: regular members of OECD, that is the only country who has turned from donor receiving to donor giving country.

13:31.886 --> 13:42.291
[SPEAKER_13]: So it's not only the Korean people, there are many developing countries who are really working hard to overcome their difficulties.

13:42.971 --> 13:49.394
[SPEAKER_13]: I think Korea can show the examples to become a donor giving country.

13:50.243 --> 13:52.785
[SPEAKER_13]: that we are very much proud of that.

13:53.866 --> 14:03.413
[SPEAKER_13]: Korea now understands the value of multilateral diplomacy perhaps more deeply than any other one else.

14:04.554 --> 14:12.620
[SPEAKER_13]: Korea will remain your most steadfast partner as you embark on this bold journey.

14:13.581 --> 14:17.424
[SPEAKER_13]: And I personally will always be in your corner.

14:18.613 --> 14:32.341
[SPEAKER_13]: I sincerely hope that the conversation to be held here in Jeju right now will serve as a guiding compass for the next Secretary General and for all harmony.

14:33.402 --> 14:38.705
[SPEAKER_13]: To each of the proud candidates, again, I don't envy you.

14:39.125 --> 14:41.887
[SPEAKER_13]: I don't know why I repeat this message to you.

14:43.463 --> 14:48.025
[SPEAKER_13]: because you may soon be frustrated from day two.

14:48.345 --> 14:49.825
[SPEAKER_13]: Day one, you will be very happy.

14:50.165 --> 14:52.446
[SPEAKER_13]: Day two, be prepared for that.

14:53.606 --> 14:56.187
[SPEAKER_13]: And yet, again, I envy you.

14:56.808 --> 14:57.388
[SPEAKER_13]: I envy you.

14:57.708 --> 15:00.929
[SPEAKER_13]: I give you my full support, full, you know, support.

15:01.449 --> 15:06.771
[SPEAKER_13]: I wish you courage, clarity of vision, and great succession.

15:07.331 --> 15:08.331
[SPEAKER_13]: It's very important.

15:08.391 --> 15:09.992
[SPEAKER_13]: You are already global citizens.

15:10.899 --> 15:15.221
[SPEAKER_13]: with global vision, global season, act like a global season.

15:15.861 --> 15:18.923
[SPEAKER_13]: Again, ladies and gentlemen, thank you very much.

15:20.063 --> 15:21.764
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you very much.

15:21.784 --> 15:22.364
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

15:23.084 --> 15:25.005
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you very much.

15:25.045 --> 15:25.385
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

15:25.405 --> 15:26.946
[SPEAKER_13]: Thank you.

15:37.031 --> 15:39.392
[SPEAKER_10]: And what excellent advice.

15:39.672 --> 15:52.116
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, as a true son of Korea and one of the most respected voices in global diplomacy, we are so grateful for your presence here today, of course, Secretary General Ban Ki-moon.

15:52.636 --> 16:01.940
[SPEAKER_10]: And next up, it is my pleasure to invite the Foreign Minister of the Republic of Korea, His Excellency Cho Hyun, to deliver his remarks.

16:02.460 --> 16:03.100
[SPEAKER_10]: Minister, please.

16:15.325 --> 16:18.106
[SPEAKER_12]: Good afternoon, ladies and gentlemen, excellencies.

16:19.647 --> 16:27.892
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, it is an honor to address this distinguished people here in Jeju.

16:28.592 --> 16:38.397
[SPEAKER_12]: Looking at the candidates gathered here, I cannot help but feel a profound sense of deja vu.

16:38.998 --> 16:41.219
[SPEAKER_12]: Although Secretary General Pan

16:42.517 --> 16:47.841
[SPEAKER_12]: said that there had been no such beauty contest at the time, at his time.

16:48.381 --> 16:49.202
[SPEAKER_12]: There was one.

16:51.744 --> 16:54.946
[SPEAKER_12]: So it takes me to 20 years ago.

16:55.607 --> 17:05.494
[SPEAKER_12]: I was accompanying then Foreign Minister Pan to Davos, the first and the only beauty contest held in Davos.

17:07.015 --> 17:11.138
[SPEAKER_12]: And at the airport, when I had a chance,

17:12.415 --> 17:16.260
[SPEAKER_12]: I said to him an unsolicited advice.

17:17.541 --> 17:28.073
[SPEAKER_12]: Minister, whichever questions I address to you, make your answer short, sweet, and simple.

17:29.694 --> 17:32.738
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, despite my advice,

17:34.357 --> 17:39.479
[SPEAKER_12]: He gave enough long, sophisticated, eloquent answers.

17:40.619 --> 17:42.400
[SPEAKER_12]: And the rest is history.

17:45.160 --> 17:48.722
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, so I talked to the candidates.

17:49.682 --> 17:58.665
[SPEAKER_12]: Speak up and show your true colors, as did Secretary General Ban Ki-moon 20 some years ago.

18:00.325 --> 18:01.626
[SPEAKER_12]: On a serious note,

18:02.815 --> 18:09.619
[SPEAKER_12]: I am compelled to compare the challenges of the time and now.

18:10.960 --> 18:18.605
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, we had war in the Middle East.

18:18.685 --> 18:22.307
[SPEAKER_12]: The war in Iraq just finished at the time.

18:22.928 --> 18:30.593
[SPEAKER_12]: Now we have the war in Iran at the critical inflection point.

18:32.403 --> 18:36.564
[SPEAKER_12]: Back then, the civil war in Darfur just finished.

18:36.864 --> 18:42.725
[SPEAKER_12]: Now, today, Sudan continues to be raged by internal war.

18:44.026 --> 18:52.047
[SPEAKER_12]: 20 years ago, achieving MDGs felt so ambitious, too ambitious.

18:53.668 --> 18:59.249
[SPEAKER_12]: Today, achieving SDG seems to be ever more elusive.

19:01.465 --> 19:15.437
[SPEAKER_12]: In that respect, I think we have been fragmented, unlike the catchphrasing word of reinventing the fragmented world.

19:16.578 --> 19:18.659
[SPEAKER_12]: So what is to be done?

19:20.201 --> 19:22.603
[SPEAKER_12]: The only big difference is that

19:24.010 --> 19:31.837
[SPEAKER_12]: The United Nations today has become more and more invisible, less and less visible.

19:32.357 --> 19:41.765
[SPEAKER_12]: So it should be the job of the next Secretary General to make it visible and lead the world.

19:43.026 --> 19:51.433
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, in several months' time, one of the five candidates will emerge, the Secretary General of the United Nations.

19:53.764 --> 20:01.327
[SPEAKER_12]: She or he will jump into the cockpit of the world plane.

20:03.008 --> 20:17.715
[SPEAKER_12]: And I think all of you are qualified, but whoever climbs the rudder to the cockpit will say to the rest of the world,

20:19.185 --> 20:24.407
[SPEAKER_12]: to go through this turbulence, fasten your seatbelt.

20:26.387 --> 20:43.253
[SPEAKER_12]: Well, since this will be the most unenviable job, as said by Secretary General Ban Ki-moon, we all owe our thanks to you for your courage in stepping up.

20:43.273 --> 20:45.954
[SPEAKER_12]: I look forward to hearing from you.

20:46.394 --> 20:47.114
[SPEAKER_12]: Thank you very much.

20:52.382 --> 20:54.623
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you so much, Minister Cho.

20:55.284 --> 20:58.985
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, some brave candidates indeed, as we've been hearing.

20:59.726 --> 21:10.551
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, we're going to move on to our candidates who are vying to become a Secretary General, but one of them couldn't be with us here today, and that is Michelle Bachelet.

21:10.631 --> 21:13.753
[SPEAKER_10]: She has kindly sent us a video message instead.

21:14.093 --> 21:19.656
[SPEAKER_10]: She is, of course, the former President of Chile and the former United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights.

21:19.996 --> 21:21.157
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's hear her message.

21:22.665 --> 21:29.029
[SPEAKER_03]: Excellencies, dear friends, I deeply regret not being able to join you in person today.

21:29.709 --> 21:31.670
[SPEAKER_03]: A scheduling conflict made it impossible.

21:32.191 --> 21:47.360
[SPEAKER_03]: I hope we will have new opportunities to talk about peace and youth soon, but I did not want to miss this moment because what you are discussing matters enormously and it connects directly to why I am running for Secretary General.

21:49.138 --> 21:58.346
[SPEAKER_03]: The United Nations was built on a simple but radical idea that nations, however different, can choose cooperation over confrontation.

21:58.926 --> 22:06.092
[SPEAKER_03]: That idea is under pressure today, but I have spent my life proving that dialogue can achieve what force never will.

22:06.853 --> 22:15.220
[SPEAKER_03]: Multilateralism is dialogue in practice, and building consensus, even when it seems impossible, is what I have done my entire life.

22:15.820 --> 22:22.484
[SPEAKER_03]: as president of Chile twice, as founding executive director of the UN Women, and as high commissioner for human rights.

22:24.145 --> 22:26.967
[SPEAKER_03]: The question is not whether we need multilateralism.

22:27.287 --> 22:28.828
[SPEAKER_03]: The question is what kind?

22:29.749 --> 22:42.717
[SPEAKER_03]: One that prevents crisis before they explode, one that amplifies the voices of all the member states of the UN, and one that is firmly anchored in the principles and values of the UN Charter.

22:43.877 --> 22:56.729
[SPEAKER_03]: Strengthening that cooperation requires a secretary general who knows when to facilitate, who can build the room where agreement becomes possible, hold the channel open when parties refuse to speak.

22:57.489 --> 23:01.833
[SPEAKER_03]: That requires patience, discretion, and the trust of all sides.

23:02.494 --> 23:09.220
[SPEAKER_03]: And that trust must include everyone at the table, especially those who have been kept out of the room for too long.

23:09.945 --> 23:12.267
[SPEAKER_03]: Young people, above all, you know your communities.

23:12.347 --> 23:15.409
[SPEAKER_03]: You see what is happening on the ground.

23:15.789 --> 23:19.211
[SPEAKER_03]: You have ideas, energy, and a profound stake in getting this right.

23:20.072 --> 23:24.635
[SPEAKER_03]: We already have Resolution 2250 on youth, peace, and security.

23:25.015 --> 23:28.417
[SPEAKER_03]: We need to implement it and apply the same logic everywhere.

23:29.058 --> 23:35.362
[SPEAKER_03]: Young people must be at the table, not as observers, but as co-authors of the decisions that shape our world.

23:36.142 --> 23:42.905
[SPEAKER_03]: I also believe we cannot have peace without development, and we cannot have peace without human rights.

23:43.565 --> 23:53.730
[SPEAKER_03]: These three pillars must be treated as one, because much of what we call inevitable conflict, displacement, suffering, was actually preventable.

23:54.650 --> 23:59.732
[SPEAKER_03]: Prevention requires presence, investment, and the courage to act early.

24:01.153 --> 24:09.066
[SPEAKER_03]: That is why I offer experience, commitment and the deep conviction that the multilateralism, when it works, changes lives.

24:10.028 --> 24:14.595
[SPEAKER_03]: I look forward to continuing this conversation with you in person very soon.

24:15.436 --> 24:15.797
[SPEAKER_03]: Thank you.

24:20.723 --> 24:23.525
[SPEAKER_10]: Madame Bachelet, thank you very much for that message.

24:23.545 --> 24:32.791
[SPEAKER_10]: And now, please allow me to welcome our very brave candidates who are vying to become the next Secretary General of the United Nations.

24:33.251 --> 24:36.173
[SPEAKER_10]: And they will join us on stage in alphabetical order.

24:36.653 --> 24:44.719
[SPEAKER_10]: So, let me invite Maria Fernanda Espinosa, former President of the UN General Assembly, and Ecuador's former Foreign Minister.

24:44.819 --> 24:46.420
[SPEAKER_10]: Please join us on stage.

24:51.290 --> 24:57.295
[SPEAKER_10]: We also have Rafael Grossi, the Director General of the International Atomic Energy Agency.

24:58.435 --> 24:59.636
[SPEAKER_10]: Come and join us, please, sir.

25:02.078 --> 25:11.385
[SPEAKER_10]: And next, Rebecca Greenspan, the Secretary General of the UN Trade and Development, or UNCTAD until recently, and as well, former Vice President of Costa Rica.

25:14.428 --> 25:14.728
[SPEAKER_10]: We have

25:15.445 --> 25:23.522
[SPEAKER_10]: Carolyn Rodriguez-Brickett, Guyana's ambassador to the United Nations and former foreign minister, welcome.

25:26.539 --> 25:31.163
[SPEAKER_10]: And finally, we have Mackie Sal, former president of Senegal.

25:31.944 --> 25:38.369
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, President Sal will be speaking in French and we have interpretation available for you all.

25:39.170 --> 25:41.192
[SPEAKER_10]: So once again, welcome.

25:41.652 --> 25:47.657
[SPEAKER_10]: We heard from Secretary General Ban earlier about what brave individuals you all are.

25:47.737 --> 25:54.103
[SPEAKER_10]: We heard from the Minister Cho as well saying that this is an unenviable position, of course.

25:54.443 --> 25:57.507
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, we're going to get into the conversation in just a little bit.

25:57.547 --> 26:01.732
[SPEAKER_10]: But just before we begin, a brief word on the format.

26:02.493 --> 26:11.664
[SPEAKER_10]: Because in the interest of fairness and equal time and opportunities, each response is going to be limited to two minutes.

26:12.104 --> 26:12.725
[SPEAKER_10]: That's right.

26:13.105 --> 26:13.967
[SPEAKER_10]: That's not very much.

26:14.447 --> 26:20.089
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, if you go a little bit beyond that, I am going to have to intervene, I'm afraid, so apologies in advance.

26:20.629 --> 26:28.873
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, later in the program, I'll also be putting questions to you from the very important audience members that we have here today.

26:29.153 --> 26:32.174
[SPEAKER_10]: They are the youth representatives who've joined us.

26:32.194 --> 26:41.478
[SPEAKER_10]: And as you heard from that message from Michelle Bachelet as well, we must include them as they will inherit the world that the UN and all of us create.

26:42.501 --> 26:48.047
[SPEAKER_10]: But first, of course, we are gathered here on a very significant anniversary for Korea.

26:48.568 --> 26:52.071
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, we know many of us from Korea will know what that is.

26:52.131 --> 26:54.254
[SPEAKER_10]: And that was in 1950.

26:54.334 --> 26:58.098
[SPEAKER_10]: This was the day of the outbreak of the Korean War.

26:58.538 --> 27:04.424
[SPEAKER_10]: Of course, the legacy of that makes us even more determined to achieve peace.

27:05.085 --> 27:20.382
[SPEAKER_10]: by all means and Jeju is as a result of that become famous the world over as the island of peace and of course it is also a place of extraordinary natural beauty so I'd like to begin with a very simple question

27:21.370 --> 27:28.480
[SPEAKER_10]: What is the one experience you've had here in Jeju that has particularly stayed with you?

27:28.860 --> 27:31.364
[SPEAKER_10]: And you have one minute for this question.

27:31.384 --> 27:36.631
[SPEAKER_10]: This is just testing your timekeeping to begin with, but one minute for this one, and later you'll have two minutes.

27:36.651 --> 27:37.652
[SPEAKER_10]: So let's start with you, Maria.

27:38.153 --> 27:38.934
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, thank you.

27:39.014 --> 27:40.435
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you to the organizers.

27:40.615 --> 27:47.000
[SPEAKER_04]: And I have to say, yes, my heart beating because of the beauty of the place, because of the kindness of its people.

27:47.400 --> 27:57.068
[SPEAKER_04]: But I have to say one thing that I have kept deep in my heart is the Xenial women.

27:57.989 --> 28:05.395
[SPEAKER_04]: These are women from this island that go down deep in the sea to harvest seafood.

28:06.297 --> 28:13.821
[SPEAKER_04]: And they can be in the water for more than 10 minutes without an oxygen tank.

28:14.502 --> 28:15.803
[SPEAKER_04]: This is unbelievable.

28:15.923 --> 28:27.970
[SPEAKER_04]: And it shows the knowledge, the wisdom, the resilience, the quiet leadership that I see and recognize very much in the soul of the Korean people.

28:28.410 --> 28:35.354
[SPEAKER_04]: So kudos for the Haneul women that have shown endurance, resilience,

28:35.795 --> 28:36.676
[SPEAKER_04]: in deep knowledge.

28:36.816 --> 28:37.797
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm touched by that.

28:38.759 --> 28:39.299
[SPEAKER_04]: Fantastic.

28:39.319 --> 28:40.921
[SPEAKER_10]: You've kept to your minute, Rafael.

28:43.264 --> 28:43.805
[SPEAKER_14]: Thank you very much.

28:43.925 --> 28:44.646
[SPEAKER_14]: Great to be here.

28:45.827 --> 28:55.859
[SPEAKER_14]: Indeed, we know the history, we know what this place represents in good and bad, and the fact that it has become a place that represents peace

28:57.035 --> 28:57.596
[SPEAKER_14]: says it all.

28:59.356 --> 29:06.259
[SPEAKER_14]: But the one thing I was very happy about is that in record time I got an ID.

29:07.540 --> 29:21.506
[SPEAKER_14]: And in these times where welcoming people and protecting people becomes really challenging, that speaks miles about the welcoming attitude

29:22.390 --> 29:29.115
[SPEAKER_14]: And having us for this debate, which we are all looking forward to, is unique.

29:29.155 --> 29:32.497
[SPEAKER_14]: So looking forward to listen to my colleagues and having my pit as well.

29:32.537 --> 29:33.358
[SPEAKER_14]: One minute's up.

29:33.418 --> 29:34.178
[SPEAKER_14]: Fantastic.

29:34.258 --> 29:34.819
[SPEAKER_10]: That's great.

29:35.099 --> 29:35.699
[SPEAKER_10]: Efficiency.

29:35.739 --> 29:36.280
[SPEAKER_10]: We like that.

29:37.240 --> 29:37.581
[SPEAKER_10]: Rebecca.

29:38.578 --> 29:53.106
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, really, yesterday, the children that sang to us and hugged us and remind us of the warmth and the welcoming of the people of Korea, they were so wonderful.

29:53.947 --> 30:05.334
[SPEAKER_05]: And at the same time, looking at that and thinking about these children, wonderful children, you have to remind everybody of why we are here, yes?

30:05.434 --> 30:07.175
[SPEAKER_05]: Because there are many children in the world.

30:07.815 --> 30:17.142
[SPEAKER_05]: that are going through war, through hunger, through health issues and disease.

30:17.783 --> 30:33.635
[SPEAKER_05]: And so let's all come together again to cooperate, to really save all the children of the world, to really make the children that we saw yesterday the norm and not the exception.

30:34.416 --> 30:34.916
[SPEAKER_05]: Wonderful.

30:34.956 --> 30:35.556
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

30:35.597 --> 30:36.117
[SPEAKER_05]: And Carolyn?

30:36.864 --> 30:37.805
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you, Sharon.

30:38.505 --> 30:39.006
[SPEAKER_02]: Three things.

30:39.726 --> 30:49.595
[SPEAKER_02]: First, it was the stone walls last evening, and between those stone walls there were spaces, and I see that as deltas for progress, even when there is a wall.

30:50.404 --> 30:56.365
[SPEAKER_02]: Secondly, the rain, like a sense of renewal yesterday, today.

30:56.785 --> 31:00.466
[SPEAKER_02]: And thirdly, the greenery, just beautiful as well.

31:01.106 --> 31:04.767
[SPEAKER_02]: Greenery that we would all like to see all over our countries.

31:04.827 --> 31:09.248
[SPEAKER_02]: And I come from a country with 80% forest cover, so I was at home.

31:09.808 --> 31:14.109
[SPEAKER_02]: And lastly, just the hospitality of the Korean people.

31:14.289 --> 31:17.070
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

31:17.130 --> 31:17.650
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

31:17.670 --> 31:18.830
[SPEAKER_10]: And finally, Mackie.

31:19.627 --> 31:22.368
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

31:22.848 --> 31:35.370
[SPEAKER_11]: Dear Secretary General and the government of Korea, most people come to Jeju and see the beautiful of this island.

31:36.970 --> 31:46.792
[SPEAKER_11]: As a geologist, I come to Jeju and I see the beautiful volcano, beautiful rocks,

31:48.431 --> 31:59.218
[SPEAKER_11]: that shows that this island was created by huge and powerful forces below surface.

32:00.899 --> 32:06.122
[SPEAKER_11]: That's why today we all know Jeju as the land of peace.

32:08.303 --> 32:13.066
[SPEAKER_11]: That is why I'm honored and very excited to be here with all candidates.

32:13.858 --> 32:18.782
[SPEAKER_11]: and I congratulate them to talk about what we have together.

32:19.302 --> 32:24.547
[SPEAKER_11]: This fragmented world, I hope we will have a very dynamic and very positive discussion.

32:24.807 --> 32:25.227
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

32:25.527 --> 32:26.048
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderful.

32:26.128 --> 32:29.010
[SPEAKER_10]: So from the perspective of a geologist, how wonderful to hear that.

32:30.131 --> 32:32.713
[SPEAKER_10]: Brilliant, so the first starter question out of the way.

32:32.873 --> 32:50.586
[SPEAKER_10]: This is now where we get to the real gist of the conversation and it is what we've heard this morning as well from Secretary General Ban Ki-moon, the issue of multilateralism being so much under strain and we know that the system globally is fragmented at the moment.

32:50.646 --> 32:53.768
[SPEAKER_10]: I don't need to list it out, there are so many things happening right now.

32:54.529 --> 32:58.872
[SPEAKER_10]: Lots of growing questions about whether existing institutions like the UN

32:59.392 --> 33:00.792
[SPEAKER_10]: are fit for purpose.

33:00.912 --> 33:08.354
[SPEAKER_10]: So alphabetically again, I'm going to start with you Maria, because many people believe of course that the UN system is becoming ineffectual.

33:08.594 --> 33:14.955
[SPEAKER_10]: It's a lot less effective, particularly as divisions between major powers deepen.

33:15.735 --> 33:23.237
[SPEAKER_10]: What do you see as the greatest weakness in today's multilateral system and how do you plan to fix it?

33:24.157 --> 33:24.577
[SPEAKER_10]: Two minutes.

33:25.432 --> 33:26.092
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, thank you.

33:26.132 --> 33:30.533
[SPEAKER_04]: First of all, I think that we have always experienced division in the world.

33:31.474 --> 33:34.274
[SPEAKER_04]: The UN was born out of division.

33:35.775 --> 33:41.036
[SPEAKER_04]: I think the context is perhaps different today after 80 years of history.

33:41.616 --> 33:45.037
[SPEAKER_04]: And I would like to mention three key words because time is short.

33:46.058 --> 33:49.138
[SPEAKER_04]: What are the issues that we need to rebuild and restore?

33:49.839 --> 33:53.600
[SPEAKER_04]: Because we're very good at diagnosis and less good at solutions.

33:54.300 --> 33:54.900
[SPEAKER_04]: Number one,

33:56.638 --> 33:57.559
[SPEAKER_04]: is trust.

33:58.520 --> 34:11.272
[SPEAKER_04]: We really need to rebuild trust in the organization, trust among member states, and trust between the secretary general and the secretariat and the member states.

34:12.053 --> 34:23.080
[SPEAKER_04]: And this is done if you are perceived, not just say, but just perceived as an impartial, honest broker.

34:23.941 --> 34:35.148
[SPEAKER_04]: Impartiality means that you can be legitimate to all, serve all, and bring all the parties together.

34:36.048 --> 34:41.892
[SPEAKER_04]: You have to be a Secretary General partial only to the Charter and to international law.

34:42.352 --> 34:45.694
[SPEAKER_04]: The second key word is performance.

34:46.574 --> 34:52.238
[SPEAKER_04]: I think the UN is experiencing the biggest implementation gap in history.

34:52.938 --> 35:13.143
[SPEAKER_04]: the promises that are written in the charter, the commitments we sign, the resolutions we adopt, and yet the people on the ground are not seeing how the UN is improving their daily lives, how they live in a safer environment, how they can look at the future with hope.

35:13.923 --> 35:19.664
[SPEAKER_04]: So to close the implementation gap, I would use another key word, accountability.

35:20.445 --> 35:21.405
[SPEAKER_04]: Accountability.

35:22.725 --> 35:28.027
[SPEAKER_04]: There is the need for a new and renewed accountability infrastructure.

35:28.407 --> 35:34.389
[SPEAKER_04]: And the third, my time is up, but at least I would just mention, convene and partner.

35:35.030 --> 35:49.735
[SPEAKER_04]: The UN is the beating heart of multilateralism, but has the responsibility and the legitimacy to bring all regions, all actors, banks, the private sector, and of course member states

35:50.155 --> 35:54.017
[SPEAKER_04]: together to solve the current challenges of our times.

35:54.117 --> 35:54.698
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderful.

35:54.818 --> 36:01.542
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for almost meeting your two-minute mark and it's all about trust, performance and convening, which is your three points.

36:02.242 --> 36:10.206
[SPEAKER_10]: Rafael, I'm going to come to you about another issue that came up this morning in the leadership conversation and that is about the smaller groupings.

36:10.246 --> 36:14.469
[SPEAKER_10]: We heard a lot about ASEAN from the former Indonesian president as well as from

36:15.029 --> 36:26.456
[SPEAKER_10]: Secretary General Ban Ki-moon, those smaller groupings such as G20, all the other alliances out there, MIKTO as well we heard about, they are all there to tackle global challenges.

36:26.496 --> 36:32.540
[SPEAKER_10]: So do these arrangements strengthen the UN or do they risk sidelining it?

36:33.284 --> 36:34.305
[SPEAKER_14]: can go both ways.

36:35.026 --> 36:36.828
[SPEAKER_14]: The thing is how we go about it.

36:37.368 --> 36:44.775
[SPEAKER_14]: The existence and the presence of other groupings and then you could of course categorize this in many different ways.

36:46.057 --> 36:50.081
[SPEAKER_14]: You have organizations, institutions that do exist, including within

36:50.721 --> 36:54.823
[SPEAKER_14]: the UN system which did not exist back in 1945.

36:55.564 --> 37:19.738
[SPEAKER_14]: But you have these groupings and often one hears this argument that you are putting across that the UN perhaps is not reflecting the world as it is and why should it when we have the G7 or the G20 or the BRICS or the Shanghai Cooperation Organization or the Organization of Islamic Cooperation and we could continue

37:20.398 --> 37:21.199
[SPEAKER_14]: enumerating them.

37:22.079 --> 37:33.766
[SPEAKER_14]: The existence of these groupings I see as a strength in the sense that they reflect a number of circumstances.

37:34.667 --> 37:42.151
[SPEAKER_14]: In some cases, it's a grouping that came together because of a specific situation, like the G20 after the 2008 crisis.

37:42.531 --> 37:43.852
[SPEAKER_14]: In some other cases, like the

37:46.493 --> 37:48.054
[SPEAKER_14]: before G7.

37:48.434 --> 37:52.936
[SPEAKER_14]: Now it is a political, strategic evolution.

37:54.076 --> 38:03.320
[SPEAKER_14]: BRICS is a reply to the gathering of other types of developed economies.

38:03.520 --> 38:14.445
[SPEAKER_14]: So all of this is there, and through them we can at the UN system or from the UN system get

38:15.805 --> 38:20.628
[SPEAKER_14]: views that are reflecting this particular set of problems.

38:21.428 --> 38:30.693
[SPEAKER_14]: But at the end of the day, at the end of the day, the UN continues to be the only sole global platform.

38:30.933 --> 38:38.576
[SPEAKER_14]: Because all these groupings in all their beauty and effectiveness cannot reflect global preoccupations.

38:38.756 --> 38:39.297
[SPEAKER_14]: They reflect

38:39.897 --> 38:46.523
[SPEAKER_14]: Partial visions and rightly so but this is why we have and we will continue to have the UN

38:47.437 --> 38:48.458
[SPEAKER_10]: Well said, thank you.

38:49.278 --> 38:58.443
[SPEAKER_10]: Rebecca Greenspan, we've heard a lot about issues such as climate change, artificial intelligence as well is a key one, as well as global health.

38:58.463 --> 39:02.205
[SPEAKER_10]: Of course, we've come out of the pandemic a few years ago, we know how that ended.

39:02.945 --> 39:15.391
[SPEAKER_10]: So how should the UN work more closely, and particularly in your role at UNCTAD, you must have done very closely with the private sector, while of course maintaining its independence and legitimacy?

39:16.492 --> 39:28.676
[SPEAKER_05]: Yeah, let me first say that part of the thing with the global challenges is that we can fragment our actions, but we cannot fragment our problems.

39:29.496 --> 39:34.837
[SPEAKER_05]: And that's why we have to get together to be able to solve the problems.

39:35.358 --> 39:39.539
[SPEAKER_05]: When we act alone, we don't solve the problems, we just deepen them.

39:40.379 --> 39:46.264
[SPEAKER_05]: And with respect to the partnering, I really believe that the UN has to change the culture.

39:47.184 --> 39:50.967
[SPEAKER_05]: We think that everything has to happen in the UN.

39:51.688 --> 39:55.611
[SPEAKER_05]: And this 2026 is different than 1945.

39:57.372 --> 39:59.794
[SPEAKER_05]: In a good sense, too.

39:59.934 --> 40:03.638
[SPEAKER_05]: In 1945, maybe, all the capacities were in the UN.

40:04.258 --> 40:06.880
[SPEAKER_05]: But today, countries have more capacities.

40:07.241 --> 40:10.624
[SPEAKER_05]: There are new regional organizations that have capacities.

40:10.984 --> 40:14.767
[SPEAKER_05]: The private sector and the civil society has more capacities.

40:15.188 --> 40:18.150
[SPEAKER_05]: So we have to learn to partner.

40:18.891 --> 40:23.295
[SPEAKER_05]: As I say, the UN is unique, but it's not alone.

40:24.360 --> 40:45.604
[SPEAKER_05]: So we need to include the private sector in the conversation, especially, for example, in the frontier of knowledge and the frontier of technology for responsible AI and to close the gaps in the digital space to be able to face global health and the global challenges.

40:46.004 --> 40:48.285
[SPEAKER_05]: So we need to include the private sector.

40:48.505 --> 40:55.271
[SPEAKER_05]: Obviously, we have to do our due diligence, but we won't lose independence in doing that.

40:55.391 --> 41:00.936
[SPEAKER_05]: On the contrary, if we don't do that, we will lose relevance.

41:01.497 --> 41:03.699
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think that that's really the challenge.

41:04.159 --> 41:12.907
[SPEAKER_05]: The UN has to learn how to partner with the private sector, not only in asking for resources, but in harnessing the capacities

41:13.267 --> 41:23.544
[SPEAKER_05]: and the knowledge that is there with them and with, as I said, civil society, regional organizations that can really help the UN to get better.

41:23.982 --> 41:24.542
[SPEAKER_10]: Well done.

41:24.602 --> 41:27.383
[SPEAKER_10]: So partnership with the private sector, absolutely crucial.

41:27.703 --> 41:33.844
[SPEAKER_10]: Carolyn, turning to you next, the UN, of course, we've heard is under growing financial pressure.

41:34.424 --> 41:36.664
[SPEAKER_10]: There's lots of reforms that are being put in place.

41:36.704 --> 41:38.745
[SPEAKER_10]: They remain a major challenge as well.

41:39.145 --> 41:46.206
[SPEAKER_10]: So as secretary general, what are the two areas that you would protect above and beyond at all costs?

41:46.646 --> 41:53.007
[SPEAKER_10]: And what is the one part of the system that you are prepared to change significantly?

41:54.721 --> 41:55.501
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

41:55.561 --> 41:57.742
[SPEAKER_02]: That's giving a lot of power to the Secretary General.

41:58.643 --> 42:10.348
[SPEAKER_02]: But let me say that what we have learned during this reform process is that the resident coordinator system on the ground has improved delivery

42:11.180 --> 42:11.840
[SPEAKER_02]: by the UN.

42:12.581 --> 42:18.704
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that as we go forward in this reform process, we must protect that and we must strengthen that.

42:19.325 --> 42:26.709
[SPEAKER_02]: And what I've been hearing as well from the largest donors to the UN is that they would like to see more impact on the ground.

42:27.309 --> 42:30.571
[SPEAKER_02]: And this is one way of having impact on the ground.

42:31.051 --> 42:36.094
[SPEAKER_02]: So I would say that is one thing that we should protect and we should strengthen.

42:36.950 --> 42:46.955
[SPEAKER_02]: I wouldn't want to preempt the decision of member states in terms of the structural reforms, because that reform will change the face of what the UN looks like.

42:47.455 --> 42:57.240
[SPEAKER_02]: But what I think is important to do is to make sure that member states have all the information that they need to make evidence-based decisions.

42:57.620 --> 43:00.642
[SPEAKER_02]: So whether they decide to merge UN agencies

43:01.222 --> 43:08.107
[SPEAKER_02]: or to merge functions, for example, that it must be guided by evidence-based information.

43:08.448 --> 43:11.510
[SPEAKER_02]: So that is something that I would certainly want to see.

43:12.050 --> 43:19.116
[SPEAKER_02]: Now, it is highly likely that by the time the new Secretary General is there, some of these decisions are already made.

43:19.576 --> 43:21.497
[SPEAKER_02]: and so it's a matter of implementation.

43:21.997 --> 43:33.464
[SPEAKER_02]: But I also believe that in any organization, much less one that is 80 years old, that reform must be a continuous process and adjustments must be a continuous process.

43:33.904 --> 43:43.350
[SPEAKER_02]: The developments that we have seen over these last five, six years in terms of AI and so on, the developments before that would have taken decades.

43:43.630 --> 43:44.831
[SPEAKER_02]: This one is just...

43:45.591 --> 43:47.373
[SPEAKER_02]: took just a few years.

43:47.754 --> 43:52.400
[SPEAKER_02]: And so we have to be prepared to be dynamic and to move with the times and to change with the times.

43:53.333 --> 43:53.753
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderful.

43:53.813 --> 43:54.914
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that, Carolyn.

43:55.634 --> 44:06.958
[SPEAKER_10]: Finally, President Maguizal, of course, many countries in the Global South, yours included, argue that the UN still very much reflects the power structures of the past.

44:07.338 --> 44:15.100
[SPEAKER_10]: So what specific change would you make to the organization, as Secretary General, for it to be more responsible and more responsive?

44:15.661 --> 44:16.581
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you very much.

44:16.601 --> 44:19.822
[SPEAKER_11]: I would like to start

44:21.460 --> 44:28.207
[SPEAKER_08]: I would like to begin with the date of birth of the United Nations, 1945.

44:28.227 --> 44:30.329
[SPEAKER_08]: We were 51 countries assigned.

44:34.485 --> 44:50.837
[SPEAKER_08]: Now we are 193 countries and the organization is working still in the same way, which shows that there is a gap between what the world has become and what the organization used to be and that gap.

44:51.838 --> 44:59.724
[SPEAKER_08]: It's even more important nowadays that we are facing even bigger challenges.

45:00.284 --> 45:10.291
[SPEAKER_08]: Those tangible things are terrorism, for example, security-related challenges, artificial intelligence, the less access of peoples

45:13.433 --> 45:19.058
[SPEAKER_08]: and to knowledge or financing also the violations of human rights.

45:19.578 --> 45:36.793
[SPEAKER_08]: That is why we need to change the organization because it is an important platform and it is the only one and it is a universal platform that has a vocation to put the world around one table and to decide about the future of the world.

45:37.353 --> 46:01.789
[SPEAKER_08]: And in order to bring about solutions to these challenges, I believe that we need a change, a shift in paradigm by a new redistribution, a fair redistribution, and it assumes that we have capital market access, financial markets,

46:02.389 --> 46:04.390
[SPEAKER_08]: not only that, but also technologies.

46:04.710 --> 46:12.034
[SPEAKER_08]: We talk a lot about artificial intelligence, but it shouldn't be something that is reserved to privileged countries.

46:12.094 --> 46:14.715
[SPEAKER_11]: That is why we need to reform the organization.

46:14.735 --> 46:19.457
[SPEAKER_08]: First of all, the secretariat, and then also the institution.

46:19.817 --> 46:30.963
[SPEAKER_08]: But I believe also that member states have to participate in this reform, and of course, opening the Security Council and our working ways.

46:31.083 --> 46:31.763
[SPEAKER_08]: Thank you very much.

46:32.043 --> 46:32.783
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

46:33.183 --> 46:36.244
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you all for keeping to your two minutes at the start.

46:36.404 --> 46:41.806
[SPEAKER_10]: And so importantly said, reallocating resources is needed at a time like this.

46:42.406 --> 46:50.128
[SPEAKER_10]: But we're now moving on very quickly, because we have limited time, of course, to the very important question of peace and security.

46:50.828 --> 47:06.051
[SPEAKER_10]: And in fact, the world, according to statistics, and of course you can turn the news on and you can find out yourself, is actually experiencing its highest number of armed conflicts since the end of the Second World War.

47:06.551 --> 47:14.453
[SPEAKER_10]: And this is a terrifying thing, and of course, which makes the role of the next Secretary General even more important and fundamental.

47:15.293 --> 47:16.253
[SPEAKER_10]: Maria, I'm turning to you.

47:16.633 --> 47:30.536
[SPEAKER_10]: Of all the crises, and there are many, as we know, facing the world today, what issue would be your top priority on day one in the job?

47:32.277 --> 47:44.079
[SPEAKER_04]: My answer would be that you cannot rank conflicts to say this conflict is more important than conflict B or C. Every place where civilians suffer

47:45.225 --> 47:56.708
[SPEAKER_04]: Every place where lives, livelihoods, hope, the future is hurt is the place for the United Nations to act and to act early.

47:58.429 --> 48:12.853
[SPEAKER_04]: That's why my campaign and my narrative is about prevention, is about early engagement, is about prevention as a culture, as a way of operating within the system.

48:14.093 --> 48:23.980
[SPEAKER_04]: I think the world wants to see a secretary general that is foot on the ground, that is present, that is persistent, that is where she needs to be.

48:24.781 --> 48:27.723
[SPEAKER_04]: And of course, this is absolutely vital.

48:28.163 --> 48:30.905
[SPEAKER_04]: When you look at what is happening in the world, you're right.

48:31.306 --> 48:36.109
[SPEAKER_04]: We are living the highest numbers of armed conflicts since the Second World War.

48:36.669 --> 48:39.892
[SPEAKER_04]: This means that perhaps the UN didn't prevent enough.

48:40.512 --> 48:44.196
[SPEAKER_04]: didn't act early enough and did not respond enough.

48:44.816 --> 48:57.248
[SPEAKER_04]: The responsibility of the Secretary General is to act early, to persist and be present, to deploy all the machinery and the infrastructure that the UN has on the ground

48:57.728 --> 49:03.049
[SPEAKER_04]: to decrease the suffering of civilian people, to protect people.

49:03.389 --> 49:09.571
[SPEAKER_04]: And when I say protect people, it includes also protecting the peacekeepers on the ground.

49:10.051 --> 49:18.513
[SPEAKER_04]: We have seen yesterday an excellent resolution approved by the Security Council because the duty of the UN is to protect people

49:19.073 --> 49:24.861
[SPEAKER_04]: to prevent conflict, to protect people, but also protect peacekeepers.

49:24.921 --> 49:37.257
[SPEAKER_04]: And here, my thoughts with the Korean peacekeepers and with the 4,500 peacekeepers that have lost their lives serving under the UN flag.

49:37.677 --> 49:42.044
[SPEAKER_04]: So no conflict is important than another conflict.

49:42.264 --> 49:51.098
[SPEAKER_04]: All conflicts are the work of the UN, the responsibility of the UN, and the responsibility of a present Secretary General.

49:51.921 --> 49:52.762
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

49:53.222 --> 49:58.427
[SPEAKER_10]: Now moving on to the big nuclear issues, and of course we have the head of the IAEA himself right here.

49:59.047 --> 50:11.658
[SPEAKER_10]: The Security Council we know is increasingly divided, and of course nuclear risks are growing as we all know, including of course the ongoing challenges that are posed by North Korea in this region.

50:12.398 --> 50:18.444
[SPEAKER_10]: So how can the UN preserve and strengthen the global non-proliferation treaty?

50:19.024 --> 50:29.198
[SPEAKER_14]: But we should remember that the creation of the UN comes in the wake of the use of nuclear weapons, and that the first resolution of the General Assembly was about it.

50:29.599 --> 50:35.687
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to see, and perhaps it's a sobering conclusion, that 80 years after that,

50:36.237 --> 50:43.824
[SPEAKER_14]: issue of nuclear weapons continue to haunt us and not in a way that seems to be going in the right direction.

50:44.645 --> 50:55.655
[SPEAKER_14]: We see that after a period, a relatively long period of gradual decrease in nuclear arsenals, this has stopped.

50:55.995 --> 50:58.698
[SPEAKER_14]: We see again the curve

51:00.299 --> 51:12.882
[SPEAKER_14]: slowly but steadily picking up the issue, of course, which resonates so vividly here in this country of the DPRK, but not only there.

51:13.543 --> 51:28.667
[SPEAKER_14]: The situations that we are trying to grapple with, coming from Burgenstock last weekend, where we are still trying to contain a problem before it becomes yet another

51:29.967 --> 51:34.209
[SPEAKER_14]: case of proliferation of nuclear weapons.

51:34.790 --> 51:56.862
[SPEAKER_14]: And what is also intriguing and concerning is that we listen more and more a conversation in countries that heretofore have abstained from having nuclear weapons, asking themselves whether this world, this fragmented world, does not warrant them reviewing

51:57.622 --> 52:13.087
[SPEAKER_14]: that in some places some are saying well the protection between quotes that we are having from countries that do have nuclear weapons perhaps is not rock solid as we thought it was so shouldn't we

52:14.067 --> 52:15.388
[SPEAKER_14]: have nuclear weapons.

52:15.568 --> 52:37.098
[SPEAKER_14]: And believe you me, although we have a few countries, nine, having nuclear weapons, the world with the degree of conflictivity that we are having, and you are quoting the number of conflicts with 20, 25 of 37 countries with nuclear weapons, would be very, very dangerous indeed.

52:38.042 --> 52:38.982
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that message.

52:39.482 --> 52:44.724
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, Rebecca, a secretary general can, of course, act quietly behind the scenes.

52:44.764 --> 52:46.805
[SPEAKER_10]: You know, quiet diplomacy is truly powerful.

52:47.285 --> 52:49.745
[SPEAKER_10]: Or, of course, they could be acting very publicly.

52:49.986 --> 52:53.667
[SPEAKER_10]: So an easy question, but potentially a complex one for you.

52:54.407 --> 52:58.328
[SPEAKER_10]: What kind of diplomacy will you rely on most as secretary general?

52:59.493 --> 53:00.554
[SPEAKER_05]: No, thank you very much.

53:01.194 --> 53:16.645
[SPEAKER_05]: Let me first say that I have proposed the need to restructure the Office of the Secretary General precisely because I think that you cannot outsource mediation and you cannot outsource active diplomacy.

53:17.285 --> 53:26.832
[SPEAKER_05]: The Secretary General has to have the capacities in the Office of the Secretary General to be able to be active, to be present, to be visible, and to be effective.

53:27.232 --> 53:28.493
[SPEAKER_05]: So, first point.

53:29.133 --> 53:30.574
[SPEAKER_05]: Second point, it depends.

53:31.134 --> 53:33.015
[SPEAKER_05]: Let me give you two examples.

53:33.035 --> 53:43.680
[SPEAKER_05]: In Sudan right now, what we need to do is to put the spotlight in Sudan, because we know that what we see, we saw in Al-Fasher can happen again.

53:44.520 --> 53:46.302
[SPEAKER_05]: So what we need is to be visible.

53:46.362 --> 53:48.184
[SPEAKER_05]: What we need is to be outspoken.

53:48.244 --> 53:53.288
[SPEAKER_05]: What we need is to call for the attention on what is happening in Sudan.

53:53.589 --> 53:57.092
[SPEAKER_05]: We need to call for a humanitarian ceasefire immediately.

53:57.552 --> 54:04.299
[SPEAKER_05]: And the UN should be an actor that will allow more coordination in the different tracks.

54:04.839 --> 54:08.182
[SPEAKER_05]: that are today in negotiating.

54:08.242 --> 54:11.125
[SPEAKER_05]: So there are many tracks of negotiation.

54:11.425 --> 54:12.646
[SPEAKER_05]: There is no coordination.

54:13.046 --> 54:15.349
[SPEAKER_05]: So we need to call it out.

54:16.430 --> 54:29.782
[SPEAKER_05]: But, for example, in the Black Sea Initiative that, as you know, I negotiated with Russia, with Ukraine, and with Turkey, precisely for that problem, we needed quiet diplomacy.

54:30.462 --> 54:39.875
[SPEAKER_05]: We needed a diplomacy that first was able to talk to the actors, see what were the possibilities, and act accordingly.

54:40.275 --> 54:46.644
[SPEAKER_05]: So in that case, quiet diplomacy was necessary, much more discrete.

54:47.004 --> 55:04.868
[SPEAKER_05]: diplomacy, to be able to have a text to negotiate without exposing anybody and do that in a context where we were not ending the war, but we were avoiding a world food crisis within a war.

55:05.308 --> 55:11.530
[SPEAKER_05]: So we were able to get an agreement because quiet diplomacy was the way to go.

55:11.850 --> 55:19.252
[SPEAKER_10]: So a combination of both, and as you mentioned, the Black Sea Initiative, where, of course, Ukrainian grain was available to move again to the rest of the world.

55:19.692 --> 55:22.513
[SPEAKER_10]: Carolyn, you know, Rebecca just mentioned Sudan.

55:22.853 --> 55:32.955
[SPEAKER_10]: We know that conflicts in those places, Sudan, Myanmar, this region, and many others, of course, tend to fade from international headlines.

55:33.475 --> 55:35.996
[SPEAKER_10]: They don't get the international attention required.

55:36.376 --> 55:41.577
[SPEAKER_10]: So how would you ensure that long-running crises are not forgotten?

55:43.998 --> 55:46.159
[SPEAKER_02]: I think there are several ways we can do this.

55:46.779 --> 55:59.625
[SPEAKER_02]: One of the things that I've noticed is that while we may have a lot of discussions in the UN on a particular crisis, the media chooses which of these crises they want to highlight.

56:00.085 --> 56:04.447
[SPEAKER_02]: And there are two or three of them that will be in the headlines all the time.

56:05.227 --> 56:14.054
[SPEAKER_02]: And so I think that we have to find better ways, the Secretary General in particular, to communicate, to communicate what is happening out there.

56:14.675 --> 56:20.900
[SPEAKER_02]: Because as we have seen in recent times, there's nothing like a frozen crisis any day one.

56:21.560 --> 56:25.004
[SPEAKER_02]: can just come at it at the top of the agenda.

56:25.665 --> 56:29.830
[SPEAKER_02]: And so communication, I think, it's very, very important to do that.

56:30.151 --> 56:32.814
[SPEAKER_02]: But not only the Secretary General.

56:33.174 --> 56:37.319
[SPEAKER_02]: We have all 193 member states represented at the UN.

56:38.020 --> 56:46.862
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that discussion with member states, whether it's in smaller groups, a crisis from a particular area, discussing with them.

56:47.303 --> 56:53.404
[SPEAKER_02]: And I've seen member states use the platforms at the UN as well to promote different issues.

56:53.664 --> 57:06.288
[SPEAKER_02]: And this is one way I think we can work together, the Secretary General and member states, to keep these, I wouldn't call them forgotten, but those that do not get the kind of global attention that they need.

57:06.888 --> 57:19.196
[SPEAKER_02]: But I'm also conscious that there are times when you have to choose whether you're going to make a public statement or you're going to do things quietly to allow for solutions to progress.

57:19.776 --> 57:32.864
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think one has to discern when that is necessary because I've also seen cases where when you come out too quickly with a public statement, you remove yourself from being part of the solution as Secretary General.

57:33.364 --> 57:35.486
[SPEAKER_02]: And so, as I said, discernment,

57:36.266 --> 57:41.389
[SPEAKER_02]: versatility and knowing which of the options you should choose for each one.

57:42.370 --> 57:43.530
[SPEAKER_10]: Good response, thank you.

57:43.630 --> 57:45.271
[SPEAKER_10]: And within two minutes too, excellent.

57:46.052 --> 57:55.417
[SPEAKER_10]: Now moving to another question and again reflecting on what Secretary General Ban Ki-moon said earlier, you know, the role of the Secretary General is so difficult.

57:55.517 --> 57:59.800
[SPEAKER_10]: It's an unenviable role and he doesn't envy you guys for going up for it.

58:00.500 --> 58:04.903
[SPEAKER_10]: There's so many difficult choices that the Secretary General has to make for the UN.

58:05.843 --> 58:11.009
[SPEAKER_10]: So how would you choose to invest the political energy?

58:11.450 --> 58:19.740
[SPEAKER_10]: Which crises do you think will deserve the UN's immediate attention and resources once you take office?

58:22.774 --> 58:40.114
[SPEAKER_06]: The first ever is to give a certain hierarchy among these different crises, because there are so many crises that threaten the peace and that requires our whole attention, and every crisis

58:42.635 --> 58:50.259
[SPEAKER_06]: that makes human suffer and that has an impact on the economic world is important.

58:50.299 --> 58:53.840
[SPEAKER_06]: So we should not rank different crises.

58:54.501 --> 59:07.627
[SPEAKER_06]: And, for example, the war in Sudan where several thousand, hundreds of millions of people die and who become refugees who suffer in

59:08.047 --> 59:10.870
[SPEAKER_06]: extreme conditions that should not be forgotten.

59:10.890 --> 59:16.815
[SPEAKER_11]: And all these crises all over the world are important.

59:16.956 --> 59:24.002
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course, there are crises that are bigger in, for example, the crisis in Israel.

59:25.944 --> 59:27.785
[SPEAKER_06]: and also the Hormuz Strait.

59:28.625 --> 59:43.410
[SPEAKER_06]: Those are big crises that have a big consequence on the global economic environment, of course, and we can think about the Russia-Ukraine crisis and different climate change.

59:44.430 --> 59:59.474
[SPEAKER_06]: We can think about bigger crises that also get a lot of attention from the media, but we should use all our diplomatic network and all our resources to prevent these conflicts and crises.

59:59.494 --> 01:00:05.896
[SPEAKER_06]: And this is the work that the Secretary General has to do, and it's the work of the UN.

01:00:06.256 --> 01:00:11.597
[SPEAKER_06]: So therefore, we have to rebuild the trust between the member states of the UN.

01:00:13.539 --> 01:00:29.593
[SPEAKER_06]: And we have to build the trust so that we can, in a responsible manner, fight against this crisis and to bring our whole world towards a future that is more stable.

01:00:31.384 --> 01:00:32.124
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

01:00:32.585 --> 01:00:39.327
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, absolutely, having to allocate all those resources to every crisis in the world is a difficult one, and rebuilding trust.

01:00:39.747 --> 01:00:47.730
[SPEAKER_10]: And speaking of rebuilding trust, we're moving on to our final theme, and that is, of course, the reason why we have so many young people amongst us in the audience.

01:00:47.850 --> 01:01:00.394
[SPEAKER_10]: It's about, of course, coming up with issues at the UN and elsewhere around technology, around development, around climate, that will impact not only the world, but

01:01:00.774 --> 01:01:08.721
[SPEAKER_10]: future generations, and this is why it's so important to be a part of this conversation that includes the young.

01:01:10.002 --> 01:01:19.289
[SPEAKER_10]: So Maria Fernanda Espinosa, young people are not only demanding change from outside the UN, many are already working from within the system.

01:01:19.790 --> 01:01:24.834
[SPEAKER_10]: How would you ensure that younger staff have a stronger voice in shaping the UN's future?

01:01:28.423 --> 01:01:33.846
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, I think I try to move away from the tokenistic approach.

01:01:34.006 --> 01:01:36.747
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, young people should participate.

01:01:37.247 --> 01:01:39.008
[SPEAKER_04]: They should be part of the solution.

01:01:39.629 --> 01:01:45.492
[SPEAKER_04]: My experience shows me that the most efficient teams are intergenerational teams.

01:01:46.752 --> 01:01:53.755
[SPEAKER_04]: to combine wisdom, institutional memory with innovation and cutting-edge knowledge.

01:01:54.195 --> 01:01:59.837
[SPEAKER_04]: So the way you build your teams has to be intergenerational.

01:01:59.877 --> 01:02:05.739
[SPEAKER_04]: Number two, younger staff members should not inherit UN as it is.

01:02:06.179 --> 01:02:11.341
[SPEAKER_04]: They should be part of the new design and the constant reform of the organization.

01:02:11.861 --> 01:02:19.047
[SPEAKER_04]: Number three, they should receive what they need in terms of a career development plan.

01:02:19.087 --> 01:02:22.409
[SPEAKER_04]: This looks like common sense, but it doesn't happen.

01:02:23.110 --> 01:02:37.661
[SPEAKER_04]: A career development plan, a skills development plan, to make sure that they are going to be fit for the role they're going to play and to really be committed with a high morale and with a sense of mission.

01:02:38.101 --> 01:02:39.522
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think that goes

01:02:40.783 --> 01:02:46.486
[SPEAKER_04]: you know, well with the UN staff, because they are the most qualified and the most committed.

01:02:46.926 --> 01:02:52.609
[SPEAKER_04]: And I think we need the human talent of the UN, and of course, young human talent.

01:02:52.949 --> 01:02:56.051
[SPEAKER_04]: Believe me, it's not an issue of looking good or of optics.

01:02:56.511 --> 01:03:03.034
[SPEAKER_04]: It is that intergenerational teams are more impactful and provide better results.

01:03:03.094 --> 01:03:09.758
[SPEAKER_04]: So of course, my team, when Secretary General, my own team and my own office,

01:03:10.178 --> 01:03:12.059
[SPEAKER_04]: is going to be intergenerational.

01:03:12.379 --> 01:03:17.381
[SPEAKER_04]: If you look at my team now, most of my advisors are under 30.

01:03:17.801 --> 01:03:19.802
[SPEAKER_04]: And one is standing over there, actually.

01:03:20.542 --> 01:03:21.543
[SPEAKER_04]: They are below 30.

01:03:21.583 --> 01:03:29.586
[SPEAKER_04]: So I fully trust the creativity, the innovation, the wisdom, the transformational capacity of younger generations.

01:03:29.987 --> 01:03:30.767
[SPEAKER_10]: Wonderfully said.

01:03:30.807 --> 01:03:33.288
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, if any of you are looking to join, there you go.

01:03:33.308 --> 01:03:35.569
[SPEAKER_10]: You can look in your cabinet if you do get the role.

01:03:37.490 --> 01:03:43.493
[SPEAKER_10]: Of course, some young people, and we've been talking a lot about this, they've lost their trust in institutions like the UN.

01:03:43.914 --> 01:03:50.357
[SPEAKER_10]: How would you rebuild trust and give young people a real crucial role in the organization?

01:03:50.937 --> 01:03:53.799
[SPEAKER_14]: First of all, they need to understand what's going on, because they don't.

01:03:54.479 --> 01:03:55.380
[SPEAKER_14]: And I don't blame them.

01:03:56.798 --> 01:04:06.506
[SPEAKER_14]: As a father of eight young adults and one teenager, I can tell you that the UN does not exist in their world.

01:04:06.826 --> 01:04:08.388
[SPEAKER_14]: They don't care about the UN.

01:04:08.408 --> 01:04:11.050
[SPEAKER_14]: And the UN basically does not care for them.

01:04:11.530 --> 01:04:13.432
[SPEAKER_14]: For everything we can say, all these phrases.

01:04:13.632 --> 01:04:15.593
[SPEAKER_14]: you were saying, you know, we have all these slogans.

01:04:17.795 --> 01:04:25.420
[SPEAKER_14]: The younger generations either don't understand, don't see the UN or don't care.

01:04:25.800 --> 01:04:28.882
[SPEAKER_14]: And so we should ask ourselves the tough questions.

01:04:29.642 --> 01:04:30.823
[SPEAKER_14]: Why is this?

01:04:32.144 --> 01:04:36.527
[SPEAKER_14]: One very important aspect, I believe, is also communication.

01:04:37.047 --> 01:04:41.170
[SPEAKER_14]: And I don't think we communicate because there are things that are important

01:04:41.610 --> 01:04:54.136
[SPEAKER_14]: for the younger generations that need to be transmitted, that they are transmitting in a very poor way, in a way that does not resonate and not through the channels that they use these days.

01:04:54.396 --> 01:05:01.139
[SPEAKER_14]: So this is, as a communicator yourself, this is a very, very important aspect, how we tell the story.

01:05:03.861 --> 01:05:10.785
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't believe that the issues of youth are solved with the creation of offices in the United Nations.

01:05:11.245 --> 01:05:15.168
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't think that is the way that doesn't move the needle.

01:05:17.750 --> 01:05:20.672
[SPEAKER_14]: Policies and good policies are by definition

01:05:21.432 --> 01:05:22.833
[SPEAKER_14]: for the younger generation.

01:05:22.853 --> 01:05:31.138
[SPEAKER_14]: When we are looking at the SDGs that Secretary Ban Ki-moon left us, who are these for?

01:05:31.719 --> 01:05:39.884
[SPEAKER_14]: I mean, when we talk about getting rid of nuclear weapons or preventing nuclear weapons or solving issues related to hunger or poverty or health,

01:05:40.324 --> 01:05:43.307
[SPEAKER_14]: we are doing this for the younger generation.

01:05:43.607 --> 01:05:54.518
[SPEAKER_14]: So I believe that trust is going to be rebuilt quite spontaneously the day they see that the UN is really solving issues and they understand how this is done.

01:05:55.361 --> 01:06:03.166
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely, and I hope that once you, and if you become Secretary General, your eight children will start to pay attention to what happens at the UN.

01:06:03.687 --> 01:06:11.672
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, Rebecca, for many young people, of course, one of the key themes we've been talking about for this entire Jeju forum is multilateralism.

01:06:12.012 --> 01:06:20.158
[SPEAKER_10]: So how would you convince young people that multilateralism truly matters and the UN truly matters in their daily lives?

01:06:21.798 --> 01:06:36.359
[SPEAKER_05]: Well, first of all, I will agree that we will rebuild their trust and we will convince them that multilateralism is important and what we do is important if we address the problem that they really face today.

01:06:37.781 --> 01:06:39.422
[SPEAKER_05]: They are worried about their jobs.

01:06:39.602 --> 01:06:41.623
[SPEAKER_05]: They are worried about quality jobs.

01:06:41.863 --> 01:06:49.986
[SPEAKER_05]: One in five young people today in the world have informal jobs, not quality jobs.

01:06:50.346 --> 01:06:51.567
[SPEAKER_05]: They are not in training.

01:06:51.667 --> 01:06:53.148
[SPEAKER_05]: They are not in education.

01:06:53.668 --> 01:06:57.049
[SPEAKER_05]: So they want to see us solving that problem.

01:06:57.089 --> 01:07:05.953
[SPEAKER_05]: They want to see us solving the problems of war that are displacing them from their own homes, from their own families.

01:07:06.313 --> 01:07:10.914
[SPEAKER_05]: So I agree that the first thing is to address the problems that they face.

01:07:11.814 --> 01:07:18.696
[SPEAKER_05]: But we also have this problem in the UN and, you know, we have a problem.

01:07:22.056 --> 01:07:30.218
[SPEAKER_05]: I ask you, do you know what is the percentage of people under 30 in the UN staff?

01:07:32.983 --> 01:07:36.807
[SPEAKER_05]: I guess four percent.

01:07:37.268 --> 01:07:37.948
[SPEAKER_05]: Four percent.

01:07:38.829 --> 01:07:46.297
[SPEAKER_05]: We have closed the doors of the UN to young people and I think that that is our first task.

01:07:46.698 --> 01:07:49.221
[SPEAKER_05]: We need to open the doors again for them.

01:07:49.601 --> 01:07:52.104
[SPEAKER_05]: They cannot even apply for the jobs.

01:07:52.504 --> 01:08:05.498
[SPEAKER_05]: You know, even the first entry point to the UN has been really almost non-existent in the last period because of financial problems.

01:08:06.038 --> 01:08:14.748
[SPEAKER_05]: So the exams for the underrepresented countries where the young people can come to the UN has not even take place.

01:08:15.348 --> 01:08:26.923
[SPEAKER_05]: So let's open the doors of the UN for young people, for them to be part of the stuff, part of the innovation, part of the idea, part of what we do every day.

01:08:27.243 --> 01:08:28.665
[SPEAKER_05]: So they will change the world.

01:08:29.066 --> 01:08:29.647
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely.

01:08:29.687 --> 01:08:31.729
[SPEAKER_10]: And of course, yes, applause, please.

01:08:32.730 --> 01:08:38.393
[SPEAKER_10]: And we need to raise that dismally low statistic, 4% of young people at the UN.

01:08:38.913 --> 01:08:42.595
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, Carolyn, of course, young people stand to benefit enormously.

01:08:42.635 --> 01:08:44.656
[SPEAKER_10]: In fact, we all do, from AI.

01:08:44.716 --> 01:08:47.517
[SPEAKER_10]: This is something that we've talked about a lot at this forum as well.

01:08:47.858 --> 01:08:49.999
[SPEAKER_10]: And responsible AI in particular.

01:08:50.019 --> 01:08:52.600
[SPEAKER_10]: But of course, young people could also not benefit

01:08:52.800 --> 01:08:53.780
[SPEAKER_10]: fit from AI.

01:08:53.800 --> 01:08:58.582
[SPEAKER_10]: There are so many jobs that may be of course non-existence for them in the future.

01:08:58.642 --> 01:09:05.785
[SPEAKER_10]: So how would you ensure that young voices will help shape the rules on artificial intelligence?

01:09:07.866 --> 01:09:08.266
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you.

01:09:09.772 --> 01:09:14.175
[SPEAKER_02]: I think that there are different ways that we can do this.

01:09:14.195 --> 01:09:20.479
[SPEAKER_02]: And just to come back to the point made earlier, I think there are two ways that we should engage young people.

01:09:20.619 --> 01:09:30.305
[SPEAKER_02]: One is getting young people in the UN system, but also in all of the processes that the UN is involved in, young people must be consulted.

01:09:30.965 --> 01:09:38.710
[SPEAKER_02]: So as shapers and also as contributors to policies that the UN is involved in.

01:09:39.630 --> 01:09:51.642
[SPEAKER_02]: I was involved, and I know Rafael says he doesn't like the creation of offices, but I was one of the co-facilitators that facilitated the process to establish the youth office.

01:09:52.418 --> 01:09:54.079
[SPEAKER_02]: of the UN.

01:09:54.099 --> 01:09:57.541
[SPEAKER_02]: And we had a consultation in Zoom.

01:09:57.701 --> 01:10:10.448
[SPEAKER_02]: 350 young people signed in from all over the world and contributed to that process and shaped that process and demanded that the head of that office is not older than 35 years old.

01:10:10.768 --> 01:10:12.789
[SPEAKER_02]: So that was one very good example.

01:10:13.429 --> 01:10:17.472
[SPEAKER_02]: In the AI governance, again, we must involve them because I think

01:10:18.612 --> 01:10:20.113
[SPEAKER_02]: not as onlookers only.

01:10:20.753 --> 01:10:28.736
[SPEAKER_02]: They're the ones, I think, that are more prone to using the technology and showing us how this could be beneficial for our world.

01:10:29.076 --> 01:10:36.059
[SPEAKER_02]: The older ones are sometimes a bit hesitant about new technology, but I think young people, they're able to tell us.

01:10:36.919 --> 01:10:44.404
[SPEAKER_02]: And one thing I've noticed in my time, and I'm still not so old, it would take 10 years to accumulate a certain amount of knowledge.

01:10:44.684 --> 01:10:46.665
[SPEAKER_02]: That now is in the hands of young people.

01:10:47.126 --> 01:10:49.767
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think they're good at analysis as well.

01:10:50.328 --> 01:11:00.394
[SPEAKER_02]: And so I agree that we shouldn't be tokenistic toward young people, as Maria said, and involve them fully in the AI governance discussion.

01:11:00.694 --> 01:11:05.157
[SPEAKER_02]: And I know that that discussion is a difficult one, but we must have young people in that as well.

01:11:05.777 --> 01:11:06.777
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

01:11:07.538 --> 01:11:20.361
[SPEAKER_10]: Now, President Makisal, with 2030 approaching, we know that will be the end of the Sustainable Development Goals and we know they will remain off track by the time we hit that target.

01:11:20.781 --> 01:11:29.763
[SPEAKER_10]: So what would come after the SDGs and what should the central priority of the next global development agenda be?

01:11:34.463 --> 01:11:39.205
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you very much.

01:11:39.385 --> 01:11:56.389
[SPEAKER_08]: After the MDGs, we followed them with the SDGs and also to fight against poverty and to protect the planet and, of course, the environment.

01:11:56.749 --> 01:12:01.730
[SPEAKER_08]: However, nowadays, the question that we have to ask ourselves is what are the challenges

01:12:02.310 --> 01:12:03.610
[SPEAKER_08]: after 2030.

01:12:03.731 --> 01:12:13.293
[SPEAKER_08]: I think that the challenges we will be facing after 2030 is resilience, mostly.

01:12:14.854 --> 01:12:24.117
[SPEAKER_08]: Resilience facing shocks that are becoming more frequent, climatic shocks, also sanitary

01:12:25.359 --> 01:12:34.529
[SPEAKER_08]: Shocks, especially after the pandemic, shocks because of the lack of financing, because of the lack of opportunities.

01:12:35.110 --> 01:12:37.673
[SPEAKER_08]: How can we organize this resilience?

01:12:37.833 --> 01:12:40.596
[SPEAKER_08]: How can we build this resilience?

01:12:40.696 --> 01:12:45.882
[SPEAKER_11]: I believe that we need to put in place a global consortium

01:12:48.463 --> 01:13:07.548
[SPEAKER_08]: so that we can go above and beyond the 2030 agenda in order to bring about the righteous answers, also in terms of financing for developing countries

01:13:10.090 --> 01:13:23.242
[SPEAKER_08]: And also, that way, with all other countries and member states, after 2030, we'll be able to set new goals and go towards them.

01:13:25.731 --> 01:13:31.334
[SPEAKER_08]: If I had one more minute talking about youth, I could talk about two things.

01:13:31.474 --> 01:13:40.679
[SPEAKER_08]: First of all, the organization that is the United Nations has to open more channels and give more opportunities to the youth.

01:13:40.699 --> 01:13:45.662
[SPEAKER_08]: But most important, among all the human beings, the population

01:13:46.742 --> 01:13:54.028
[SPEAKER_08]: that we have on our planet, about one third of them do not have the adequate education.

01:13:54.648 --> 01:14:00.192
[SPEAKER_08]: So we have to take care of the jobs for our young people.

01:14:00.212 --> 01:14:01.053
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

01:14:01.113 --> 01:14:09.359
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, absolutely, because the SDGs are so fundamental for the world that we create, that the world that the future generations will inherit.

01:14:09.780 --> 01:14:13.742
[SPEAKER_10]: And speaking about those future generations, we have them here in the audience.

01:14:14.563 --> 01:14:20.687
[SPEAKER_10]: We can now move to the questions that some of them are posing to the future Secretary-General.

01:14:20.787 --> 01:14:31.074
[SPEAKER_10]: So let me now go to our first question, which comes from Choi Hyerin, a bachelor's graduate from Jeju Halla University.

01:14:32.075 --> 01:14:33.896
[SPEAKER_10]: Hyerin, I believe you're here somewhere.

01:14:34.797 --> 01:14:40.461
[SPEAKER_10]: Can we have the microphone for you and can you pose your question to the candidates, please?

01:14:44.285 --> 01:14:45.447
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, do we have a microphone?

01:14:47.972 --> 01:14:48.873
[SPEAKER_10]: I believe I see you there.

01:14:48.913 --> 01:14:49.374
[SPEAKER_10]: Is that you?

01:14:49.495 --> 01:14:50.216
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, perfect.

01:14:50.276 --> 01:14:51.939
[SPEAKER_10]: Can somebody get her a microphone, please?

01:14:55.365 --> 01:14:55.946
[SPEAKER_10]: Can somebody there?

01:14:56.227 --> 01:14:56.667
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

01:14:57.921 --> 01:14:59.642
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you for this opportunity.

01:15:00.703 --> 01:15:13.309
[SPEAKER_07]: As a young entrepreneur in the cultural and creative sector, I frequently see how culture bridges divides far more easily than traditional politics.

01:15:13.850 --> 01:15:21.794
[SPEAKER_07]: So given today's intense geopolitical fragmentation, how would you as Secretary General

01:15:22.194 --> 01:15:37.438
[SPEAKER_07]: strategically use the cultural and creative industries as a tool to rebuild trust between conflicting nations and revitalize multilateralism from the ground up.

01:15:37.918 --> 01:15:38.438
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

01:15:39.358 --> 01:15:40.138
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Hyerin.

01:15:40.218 --> 01:15:43.119
[SPEAKER_10]: And this is, of course, open to all of you who would like to respond.

01:15:43.919 --> 01:15:45.679
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes, Maria, followed by Rebecca.

01:15:46.920 --> 01:15:47.780
[SPEAKER_10]: Maria, you start first.

01:15:48.615 --> 01:15:48.895
[SPEAKER_04]: Okay.

01:15:49.796 --> 01:15:53.699
[SPEAKER_04]: Well, first of all, thank you for that very important question.

01:15:53.899 --> 01:15:57.142
[SPEAKER_04]: Sometimes people say that culture is soft power.

01:15:58.363 --> 01:16:10.312
[SPEAKER_04]: I think culture and intercultural dialogue and the possibility of understanding the diversity of perspectives should be the hardcore of diplomacy and dialogue.

01:16:10.632 --> 01:16:12.373
[SPEAKER_04]: So it's extremely important.

01:16:13.254 --> 01:16:17.818
[SPEAKER_04]: Believe me, when I was president of the General Assembly, the day I think I was the most

01:16:18.518 --> 01:16:23.085
[SPEAKER_04]: popular is when I invited BTS to join me.

01:16:23.706 --> 01:16:34.562
[SPEAKER_04]: The K-pop culture of Korea has gone all over the world and brought a mutual understanding, energy, the ability

01:16:35.002 --> 01:16:55.651
[SPEAKER_04]: to speak to different cultures, not to speak about Korean series, which are at the heart of my own family household, but to say that a culture builds bridges is the hardcore, not the soft power, but the strong power of diplomacy and mutual understanding.

01:16:55.771 --> 01:16:58.572
[SPEAKER_04]: The role of UNESCO is absolutely critical

01:16:59.372 --> 01:17:07.982
[SPEAKER_04]: And as Secretary General, I will ensure that intercultural dialogue, that culture itself is at the center of the work we do.

01:17:08.781 --> 01:17:09.441
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely.

01:17:09.501 --> 01:17:11.782
[SPEAKER_10]: And who can beat Korean culture, right?

01:17:11.822 --> 01:17:14.263
[SPEAKER_10]: Demon hunters, BTS, you name it.

01:17:15.023 --> 01:17:15.403
[SPEAKER_10]: Rebecca?

01:17:16.543 --> 01:17:20.904
[SPEAKER_05]: Can I just make the comment that I am freezing here?

01:17:20.924 --> 01:17:23.065
[SPEAKER_05]: Not great for climate change.

01:17:23.865 --> 01:17:24.685
[SPEAKER_05]: No, no, no, no.

01:17:24.705 --> 01:17:30.227
[SPEAKER_05]: It's because we women have a lower blood pressure, you know?

01:17:30.247 --> 01:17:34.048
[SPEAKER_05]: So the problem is who controls the air conditioning?

01:17:35.729 --> 01:17:38.330
[SPEAKER_10]: Please, can we bring the temperature up, please?

01:17:42.113 --> 01:17:45.135
[SPEAKER_05]: Let me just go to the question of the young lady.

01:17:47.196 --> 01:18:00.625
[SPEAKER_05]: Let me first say that I was really glad about your question because when I reformed ANTAT, we created a special department on creative industries.

01:18:01.928 --> 01:18:13.650
[SPEAKER_05]: And I think that this is a very powerful tool, not only to maintain culture, but to allow all the workers in the cultural space to really make a living.

01:18:14.231 --> 01:18:16.231
[SPEAKER_05]: And it's very important for small countries.

01:18:16.311 --> 01:18:19.992
[SPEAKER_05]: It's very important for the islands, for example.

01:18:21.092 --> 01:18:26.073
[SPEAKER_05]: And really, creative industries are a huge part of the economy.

01:18:26.633 --> 01:18:41.499
[SPEAKER_05]: but it's not accounted for, it's not measured, and so many times we don't take the right decisions and the right policies with respect to supporting the cultural workers and the cultural actors in the country.

01:18:42.019 --> 01:18:51.543
[SPEAKER_05]: My second point, and I will completely agree with Maria on this, is that really culture allows us to share humanity.

01:18:52.063 --> 01:19:14.949
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes, is really a space where we can understand each other, we can communicate, we can exchange, and we can do something that is very central to peace, that is allow for inclusive identities, to bring to your own identity many of the other expressions in the other cultures.

01:19:15.069 --> 01:19:20.790
[SPEAKER_05]: So, really great, and thank you, thank you for bringing that to the floor.

01:19:21.430 --> 01:19:26.991
[SPEAKER_10]: We'll move to our next question and I have to say creative industries, as you say, intangible benefits of creative industries.

01:19:27.051 --> 01:19:32.912
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm a chancellor of a university that celebrates creative industries, so very, very excited about the potential for that.

01:19:33.353 --> 01:19:35.413
[SPEAKER_10]: Next up we have Musa Elhem.

01:19:35.453 --> 01:19:39.554
[SPEAKER_10]: Musa is a master's student from Sungkyunkwan University.

01:19:39.594 --> 01:19:44.115
[SPEAKER_10]: You have a question and I hope we can get the mic to you quickly because we are running out of time.

01:19:44.335 --> 01:19:44.655
[SPEAKER_10]: Musa.

01:19:47.853 --> 01:19:53.939
[SPEAKER_15]: Trust in multilateral institutions is declining, especially among young generation.

01:19:54.279 --> 01:20:05.509
[SPEAKER_15]: So my question is, what is the first concrete change you would make as a secretary general in your first year to make them believe that the UN works for them?

01:20:07.191 --> 01:20:07.691
[SPEAKER_10]: Absolutely.

01:20:08.071 --> 01:20:10.754
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's start with you, Carolyn, followed by Magiselle.

01:20:11.835 --> 01:20:13.156
[SPEAKER_02]: Thank you for that question.

01:20:13.236 --> 01:20:14.077
[SPEAKER_02]: And I think that

01:20:15.625 --> 01:20:24.184
[SPEAKER_02]: We have failed you, actually, and all the young people in not telling the story of the UN and the achievements of the UN.

01:20:25.149 --> 01:20:32.252
[SPEAKER_02]: Many do not know that when they fly in an aeroplane, that the rules of the sky, the UN is involved in that.

01:20:33.093 --> 01:20:36.974
[SPEAKER_02]: That the food standards that we set, that it is the UN there.

01:20:37.495 --> 01:20:42.517
[SPEAKER_02]: That the first responders sometimes in the humanitarian field, it's the UN there.

01:20:43.097 --> 01:20:48.200
[SPEAKER_02]: That the children and the improvement in education for them, that it was the UN there as well.

01:20:48.620 --> 01:20:50.881
[SPEAKER_02]: And so we have failed in communicating that.

01:20:51.401 --> 01:20:52.722
[SPEAKER_02]: And as we're in the 80th year,

01:20:53.682 --> 01:20:57.167
[SPEAKER_02]: The people who witnessed war back then, they have passed on.

01:20:57.788 --> 01:21:08.081
[SPEAKER_02]: And so I think communication is important in terms of what the UN has done, but also in terms of the challenges we face and the solutions as well.

01:21:08.962 --> 01:21:12.705
[SPEAKER_02]: and how young people can be involved in those solutions.

01:21:13.205 --> 01:21:23.352
[SPEAKER_02]: Because one of the things that is overlooked sometimes is that the UN is the place where we set the norms of the world that we all agree to live by.

01:21:23.912 --> 01:21:26.995
[SPEAKER_02]: And the UN is irreplaceable in that respect.

01:21:27.155 --> 01:21:30.137
[SPEAKER_02]: There's no other organization that can do that.

01:21:30.577 --> 01:21:39.342
[SPEAKER_02]: And so I think communication is important for us to make you believe in multilateralism, but also for you to choose diplomacy.

01:21:39.862 --> 01:21:40.402
[SPEAKER_11]: Thank you.

01:21:40.702 --> 01:21:44.324
[SPEAKER_11]: Macky.

01:21:44.624 --> 01:21:49.947
[SPEAKER_08]: In fact, we do have a communication issue with the youth, with the young people.

01:21:50.347 --> 01:21:54.850
[SPEAKER_08]: However, the UN for the last 80 years did a lot

01:21:57.278 --> 01:22:05.201
[SPEAKER_08]: Without the actions of the UN, I believe that the wars would be even more devastating.

01:22:06.042 --> 01:22:14.125
[SPEAKER_08]: I believe that we were able to avoid a lot of conflicts and a lot of wars because of the work that we made at the UN.

01:22:14.485 --> 01:22:18.807
[SPEAKER_08]: And every time we discuss an issue,

01:22:20.428 --> 01:22:24.731
[SPEAKER_08]: at the UN, it is because we want the humanity to advance.

01:22:24.831 --> 01:22:37.920
[SPEAKER_08]: Every time we develop a vaccine, it's for the health of the world, and it is for the young people, the young people that communicate and live throughout social media and also very new phenomena.

01:22:38.421 --> 01:22:46.807
[SPEAKER_08]: And I believe that the institutional classic and also very old and demoted communication has to change.

01:22:47.747 --> 01:23:01.627
[SPEAKER_08]: And I believe that what UN does is actually for the purpose and for the future of the new generation, except that we need to communicate that by language that the young people understand.

01:23:02.408 --> 01:23:03.288
[SPEAKER_10]: Education is key.

01:23:03.328 --> 01:23:05.529
[SPEAKER_10]: We need to earn the trust of the young people.

01:23:06.189 --> 01:23:12.151
[SPEAKER_10]: We quickly have two last questions from the young people in the audience, and then, of course, we are going to have to wrap up with the concluding remarks.

01:23:12.451 --> 01:23:19.233
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm going to go now to Duggajin Osmanaj, who's a prospective graduate student from Songkyun Kwan University.

01:23:19.293 --> 01:23:20.974
[SPEAKER_10]: Duggajin, you have a question?

01:23:22.455 --> 01:23:22.675
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

01:23:23.215 --> 01:23:23.675
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

01:23:25.008 --> 01:23:32.412
[SPEAKER_09]: The 2020s have shown that we live in a time when wars are becoming more frequent and international norms are being increasingly challenged.

01:23:33.292 --> 01:23:35.894
[SPEAKER_09]: This decade can also be called the decade of AI.

01:23:36.414 --> 01:23:49.400
[SPEAKER_09]: So my question is just simply, do you think AI can positively aid the UN, stopping conflicts from escalating, and if so, how?

01:23:50.522 --> 01:23:51.502
[SPEAKER_10]: OK, who would like to take that?

01:23:51.542 --> 01:23:53.523
[SPEAKER_10]: Rafael, would you like to mention that?

01:23:53.963 --> 01:23:55.844
[SPEAKER_14]: It can, and it can bring problems.

01:23:55.904 --> 01:23:57.385
[SPEAKER_14]: I mean, it's a double-edged sword.

01:23:57.545 --> 01:24:01.507
[SPEAKER_14]: I think it is very clear that AI is already in our lives.

01:24:01.587 --> 01:24:04.628
[SPEAKER_14]: We talk about it as it was something that is coming.

01:24:05.248 --> 01:24:07.149
[SPEAKER_14]: It's already in everything we do.

01:24:07.609 --> 01:24:13.552
[SPEAKER_14]: There are debates within the UN and international organisations as to how to

01:24:14.852 --> 01:24:16.133
[SPEAKER_14]: govern it or control it.

01:24:17.513 --> 01:24:28.898
[SPEAKER_14]: And there are already, from the supply side, groupings that have already been established among the companies or

01:24:30.859 --> 01:24:37.646
[SPEAKER_14]: producers of rare earths or cutting-edge technologies that are already organized.

01:24:38.046 --> 01:24:46.294
[SPEAKER_14]: I think we have to be prudent in this area to make sure that we strike the right balance.

01:24:47.375 --> 01:25:00.796
[SPEAKER_14]: between having the dynamism that is going to be helping economies, is going to be helping education, innovation and so forth.

01:25:02.238 --> 01:25:13.224
[SPEAKER_14]: at the same time avoiding excesses and the absence of the human in the loop factor, which is at the end of the day what we need.

01:25:15.245 --> 01:25:25.590
[SPEAKER_14]: Some people have referred to even the possibility of having an IEA for AI, which may sound flattering, but I don't agree.

01:25:26.250 --> 01:25:28.151
[SPEAKER_14]: contrary to what people may believe.

01:25:28.171 --> 01:25:42.377
[SPEAKER_14]: I think the algorithmic dimension is rather different from an area where you have nuclear material accountability and facilities that can be inspected.

01:25:42.397 --> 01:25:51.241
[SPEAKER_14]: We have to be, I think, prudent in believing that we can have systems of control that are really effective.

01:25:51.341 --> 01:25:52.522
[SPEAKER_14]: Having an illusion

01:25:53.222 --> 01:25:57.226
[SPEAKER_14]: of verification is worse than having none at all.

01:25:57.847 --> 01:25:58.528
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for that.

01:25:58.768 --> 01:26:00.770
[SPEAKER_10]: Now I'm just going to move on to the last two questions.

01:26:00.790 --> 01:26:02.191
[SPEAKER_10]: They're both from Siu Yongs.

01:26:02.392 --> 01:26:09.839
[SPEAKER_10]: So we have Siu Yong Choi, undergraduate student, Jeju National University, and Siu Yong Yang, undergraduate student from Jeju National University.

01:26:10.059 --> 01:26:14.844
[SPEAKER_10]: If you can both identify yourself, let's start with Siu Yong Choi first.

01:26:14.904 --> 01:26:15.285
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

01:26:15.816 --> 01:26:17.797
[SPEAKER_16]: Yeah, thank you for the introduction.

01:26:17.817 --> 01:26:19.558
[SPEAKER_16]: It's a pleasure to be here.

01:26:20.158 --> 01:26:34.405
[SPEAKER_16]: My question is among the many global challenges we face today and what do you think is the most overlooked issues that young people should pay more attention to?

01:26:34.745 --> 01:26:35.185
[SPEAKER_16]: Thank you.

01:26:35.525 --> 01:26:36.525
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, Siu-Yong Choi.

01:26:36.566 --> 01:26:41.588
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's get the question from Siu-Yong Yan, who is also here, and that's about the SDGs.

01:26:41.608 --> 01:26:42.388
[SPEAKER_10]: Let's hear that question.

01:26:42.408 --> 01:26:46.190
[SPEAKER_10]: We'll take both those questions and then, of course, finally conclude with your responses.

01:26:47.570 --> 01:26:49.131
[SPEAKER_10]: Siu-Yong Yang, are you here?

01:26:49.271 --> 01:26:49.851
[SPEAKER_10]: Ah, there you are.

01:26:50.932 --> 01:26:51.272
[SPEAKER_10]: Go ahead.

01:26:54.068 --> 01:27:05.498
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, Mr. Micusel already got the similar question, but as the SDGs are set to conclude in 2030, I'm curious about your vision for the future.

01:27:06.079 --> 01:27:13.766
[SPEAKER_01]: So my question is, what values do you believe should guide the next generation of the global development agenda?

01:27:14.285 --> 01:27:26.098
[SPEAKER_01]: And if you could give a name to the post 2030 development goals like MDGs or SDGs, what would it be and what do you think should be the most important priority?

01:27:27.150 --> 01:27:28.571
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you to both this year youngs.

01:27:28.611 --> 01:27:29.432
[SPEAKER_10]: Who would like to respond?

01:27:29.472 --> 01:27:30.272
[SPEAKER_10]: There are two questions.

01:27:30.453 --> 01:27:34.636
[SPEAKER_10]: One about the issues that have been overlooked that the young generation should pay attention to.

01:27:34.956 --> 01:27:39.680
[SPEAKER_10]: And the second one, what's going to succeed the Sustainable Development Goals?

01:27:40.680 --> 01:27:46.845
[SPEAKER_10]: Rebecca, I believe you put up, and Marcel and Maria, and let's do it quickly so we can get to our concluding statements.

01:27:46.945 --> 01:27:47.306
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you.

01:27:48.006 --> 01:28:02.384
[SPEAKER_05]: Let me take the second question and say that I think that the MDGs and the SDGs have been very important, but let's remember that the date of 2030 is arbitrary.

01:28:02.985 --> 01:28:10.690
[SPEAKER_05]: And if we look at the SDGs, only 18% is in track to be complied by 2030.

01:28:11.070 --> 01:28:13.812
[SPEAKER_05]: So the agenda won't be finished by 2030.

01:28:14.733 --> 01:28:17.595
[SPEAKER_05]: So I think that the priority

01:28:18.135 --> 01:28:33.794
[SPEAKER_05]: has to be to support countries that want to continue with the SDGs because they have not been a reality in their countries yet to be able to comply, to implement the agenda that continues to be an important agenda.

01:28:34.435 --> 01:28:39.578
[SPEAKER_05]: And my second point is that we have to go beyond GDP.

01:28:40.179 --> 01:28:43.981
[SPEAKER_05]: So it's a matter also of how we measure development.

01:28:44.081 --> 01:28:49.325
[SPEAKER_05]: And I am an economist, so it's rare for an economist to say GDP doesn't tell you the story.

01:28:49.905 --> 01:28:57.868
[SPEAKER_05]: we have to measure well development so we can take the right policy decisions that will benefit people.

01:28:58.068 --> 01:28:59.569
[SPEAKER_05]: So these are my two points.

01:28:59.769 --> 01:29:00.770
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you for those two points.

01:29:00.830 --> 01:29:02.110
[SPEAKER_10]: I've just been informed.

01:29:02.130 --> 01:29:03.291
[SPEAKER_10]: We've only got three minutes left.

01:29:03.351 --> 01:29:06.892
[SPEAKER_10]: I'm sorry, I thought we had extended the session, but we only have three minutes.

01:29:06.912 --> 01:29:13.355
[SPEAKER_10]: So let's just get another quick response from, I believe, Macky Sal, and then I'm going to start with the concluding sentiments at the end.

01:29:14.035 --> 01:29:14.235
[SPEAKER_10]: Yes.

01:29:14.976 --> 01:29:15.436
[SPEAKER_10]: Very good.

01:29:16.968 --> 01:29:17.548
[SPEAKER_08]: Very well.

01:29:19.730 --> 01:29:37.059
[SPEAKER_08]: So regarding the questions about the overlooked issues that young people should pay more attention to, I think not only the young people but also the governments, the public powers, and the universal organization that is the United Nations.

01:29:37.399 --> 01:29:50.827
[SPEAKER_08]: I believe that the issue of education is a fundamental issue, which is a transcendental issue, and it allows us to comprehend the entire issue of artificial intelligence.

01:29:51.187 --> 01:29:54.229
[SPEAKER_08]: We knew the digital divide at the beginning of the year 2000.

01:29:55.890 --> 01:30:05.597
[SPEAKER_08]: Nowadays, because we had a paradigm shift regarding education, Asian countries are showing us the way.

01:30:05.977 --> 01:30:15.924
[SPEAKER_08]: After the Second World War, all the Asian countries changed the paradigm in their education, which made them able to become developed countries.

01:30:16.704 --> 01:30:24.870
[SPEAKER_08]: And that is why those challenges of education will ensure the future of the younger generation to give jobs and to give

01:30:25.330 --> 01:30:26.330
[SPEAKER_10]: Thank you, merci.

01:30:26.370 --> 01:30:29.151
[SPEAKER_10]: That's right, education and of course Asia leading the way there.

01:30:29.551 --> 01:30:39.954
[SPEAKER_10]: Now we have concluding statements and I should say that there was a lottery draw that was conducted before our session here on stage so that you could all have your concluding statements.

01:30:40.354 --> 01:30:41.955
